KIN 482E Final Assignment: Exploring the Accuracy of EA Sports FIFA's Ratings¶

Source of File:¶

https://sports-statistics.com/sports-data/fifa-2022-dataset-csvs/

Overview:¶

The goal of this project is to test the accuracy of the ratings in EA Sport's popular soccer/football video game "FIFA 22". Every year EA Sports releases a new version of this game and one of the most debated topics is always people complaining about ratings, whether people are rated too highly or too low. My goal is to take this database of player ratings, perform analysis and compare to what happened in real life. I will be comparing the average squad rating for each team according to EA Sports in the Top 5 Leagues in Europe (England, Germany, Spain, Italy, France) and then seeing how these squad ratings compared with the final table/standings of each league in real life for that year. This will give me an idea as to how accurate EA Sports is at rating players and also tell me which league they are the most/least accurate at predicting

Rationale¶

The reason why I chose to do my project on this topic is because I have played FIFA games for almost all my life and I always wondered how accurate the ratings really were but before this year I never really knew how to analyze this. I want to know how accurate their predictions are for each league and which league they are most accurate at rating.

I then took this data frame and starting with premier league, developed a repeatable process on how I could take this dataframe and split it into 5 new data frames (1 for each league). I will put all of the other leagues code down below but my explanation will only cover the Premier League code, so I don't repeat myself.

Step 1:¶

  • The first step was to create a mask to apply to the dataframe that grabbed all players who's column 'league_name' was 'English Premier League', assign that to a general dataframe called 'prem' and then create a new dataframe called prem_clubs that only had the overalls of all players in the Premier League.

Step 2:¶

  • The next step was to find the lower 25% IQR of all players in the Premier League, as in the higher leagues of soccer, most teams are filled with youth players who are on the FIFA game but in real life, never actually play for the team so the odds are it would bring the ratings down. This was also extremely important to filter out for the top clubs (ex. the 'Big Six' in England are Chelsea, Arsenal, Man City, Man United, Tottenham, and Liverpool) but because they are such big clubs, they often have lots of youth players in their system so if I did not exclude them from the rankings, they would drag their teams overall down when they don't actually play for them in real life and play for youth teams which aren't included on FIFA.

  • In the case of the Premier League, this bottom 25% IQR came out to be 65 ovr which works out very well in terms of FIFA's in-game ranking system as any cards below 65 rated are considered "bronze" in rarity and would almost never be played in a top league. This system works because it makes the top clubs with very good players not have their average ranking dragged down by their plethora of youth players, and doesn't really affect the smaller teams because they aren't composed of many top players but rather are a stronger collection of average players (generally around 73-80 overall)

  • This q1 mask was then applied to a variable prem_valid_players which was then used to modify the prem dataframe to only include players that were over 65 rated

Step 3:¶

  • Next I sorted each player by team and then found the average ranking of each team according to EA Sport's FIFA ratings
  • This was done by grouping every player in the dataframe by the club_name column and then calculating the means of each team's player's overalls and then giving them a rank based on highest average overall to lowest average overall
  • Finally I had to manually add a column to the dataframe (as EA obviously doesn't have the final standings of the teams in the database released before the season even starts) that contained each team's real finish in the table. I then calculated the difference between the EA Sports predicted rankings and the real life predicted rankings to make a new column called the Difference in Predicted Finish, and then found the mean of that column to see on average how far off EA's rating system was for each team in the Premier League
In [4]:
prem_club_ratings = prem.groupby('club_name')['overall'].mean().reset_index()
prem_club_ratings['rank'] = prem_club_ratings['overall'].rank(ascending=False).astype(int)
prem_club_ratings['Real Table Finish'] = [5, 14, 13, 9, 18, 3, 12, 16, 17, 8, 2, 1, 6, 11, 20, 15, 4, 19, 7, 10]
prem_club_ratings['Difference in Predicted Finish'] = prem_club_ratings['rank'] - prem_club_ratings['Real Table Finish']
prem_avg_error=abs(prem_club_ratings.loc[:,'Difference in Predicted Finish']).mean()
prem_club_ratings

Visualizations:¶

After these steps were completed, I had all of the data I needed to form visualizations to examine the differences between EA Sport's rating system and the real life results. I will split each set of visualizations into the 5 different leagues. These visualizations I chose help me to answer my questions because they are made to have EA Sport's Ratings represent themselves (ex. ordered based on team's average FIFA overall) and then show the real order of teams while still representing those ratings. This will show how well teams stayed in that predicted order of overalls and whether or not certain teams are massively underrated or overrated by EA Sports.

Justification for why each chart is helpful is listed below in Premier League, explanation not copied on every league's visualizations so that same things aren't restated exactly the same 5 times

Premier League:¶

  • The top two visualizations showcase the teams organized based on rankings, with the point on the graph representing their average overall FIFA rating and their finish in the predicted/real life table. This is why the first graph on the left is completely uniform, it is the table based on the average FIFA rankings so with every step down in rank, the lower the overall gets. The second table shows the teams now reorganized in order of real life finish in the 21/22 Premier League Season, but still shows their overalls, and as you can see they are very much not in order anymore and some teams have drastically over/underperformed their FIFA predictions.

  • The bottom two figures represent the movement of teams between the FIFA predicted model and the real life results. The line plot on the left shows the exact positions each team was predicted to finish compared to their real finishes, while the bar chart on the right hand side shows the numerical difference between the two rankings.

Accuracy Between Leagues¶

  • With all of this data now processed and visualized, I wanted to get a sort of "final answer" to my question. I wanted to see on average how far off EA is ranking teams in each different league, and then compare them to see in this version of the game (FIFA 22), which league were they the worst at predicting
In [19]:
leagues = ['Premier League', 'Bundesliga', 'La Liga', 'Serie A', 'Ligue 1']
league_error = [prem_avg_error, bundesliga_avg_error, laliga_avg_error, seriea_avg_error, ligue1_avg_error]

avg_league_error = pd.DataFrame({'Leagues':leagues, 'Mean Error of Prediction':league_error})

#fig, axs = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,10))

sns.barplot(data=avg_league_error, x='Leagues', y='Mean Error of Prediction', dodge=False)
plt.title('Average Error of Team Ratings in Each of the Top 5 Leagues')

plt.show()

As you can see from this chart, EA Sports averages anywhere from around 2.5-3.5 places off for teams in their rankings. This number is honestly lower than I expected, but I think these visualizations actually tell a bigger story about their system. The chart above also shows that they were the most inaccurate in the Bundesliga and most accurate in the Serie A. This is a suprising result for me as EA Sports are much more heavily partnered with the Premier League (as of this year, EA Sports is one of their main sponsors, but have been on a smaller scale for a long time as well) so I assumed they would have more data available to them to make more accurate rankings.

Summary¶

Looking at the most extreme ends of the rankings, EA Sports correctly predicted the champions 3/5 times and the last-placed teams only 1/5 times, showing much more consistency at guessing the more watched/better teams, but not as much for teams with less recognition. I think that my visualizations prove that EA Sports must spend more time doing research on non-top teams as in most of my graphs, after the top 5/6 teams, there is much more variability in the predicted/real life results. This is probably partly due to the fact that all of these leagues are part of tiered systems, where teams can get relegated and promoted each year, but a lot of this inaccuracy is still falling with teams who have been in the league for multiple years. Predicting sport results is no easy feat, but for a company who has to spend the entire year, watching and collecting data in order to update their game with new ratings and rewards based on real-life results, I would expect more accuracy from these results.
